# AuthoriDex — Cursor Agent Rules

## Project Overview
AuthoriDex is a live influence index and prediction platform. It ranks 100 public figures by influence score, updated hourly via external APIs. Users vote, predict outcomes, and track momentum in real time.

## Stack
- Frontend: React 18, Vite, TailwindCSS, shadcn/ui, Wouter (routing), TanStack Query (data fetching)
- Backend: Node.js, Express, TypeScript
- Database: PostgreSQL via Supabase (Drizzle ORM)
- Hosting: Railway (backend), Vercel (frontend)
- Auth: Passport.js (local strategy)

## Folder Structure
- `client/` — React frontend
- `server/` — Express backend
- `shared/` — Shared types/schemas used by both frontend and backend
- `server/trending/` — Score engine (DO NOT modify without full understanding)
- `server/ingestion/` — Data ingestion jobs
- `server/jobs/` — Background schedulers

## Critical Rules — Read Before Every Change

### Never Do This
- NEVER push directly to `main` branch
- NEVER modify `server/db.ts` without understanding Drizzle + Supabase pooler setup
- NEVER expose `SUPABASE_SERVICE_ROLE_KEY` to the frontend
- NEVER modify the score engine (`server/trending/`) without being explicitly asked
- NEVER change scheduler timing without being explicitly asked
- NEVER delete or rename database tables without a migration plan
- NEVER commit `.env` files to git

### Always Do This
- ALWAYS create a feature branch before making changes: `git checkout -b feature/name`
- ALWAYS check `shared/` folder when changing types — changes affect both frontend and backend
- ALWAYS use TanStack Query for frontend data fetching (not raw fetch/axios)
- ALWAYS use Wouter for client-side navigation (not React Router)
- ALWAYS use existing shadcn/ui components before creating new ones
- ALWAYS preserve existing API response shapes — frontend depends on them
- ALWAYS test locally with `npm run dev` before pushing

## Code Style
- TypeScript everywhere — no `any` types unless absolutely necessary
- Functional React components only — no class components
- TailwindCSS for all styling — no inline styles
- Use existing color variables and design tokens from `tailwind.config.ts`
- Keep components small and focused — one responsibility per component
- Use `shared/schema.ts` for all Zod validation schemas

## Database Rules
- Use Drizzle ORM for all DB queries — no raw SQL unless absolutely necessary
- The `DATABASE_URL` uses Supabase Session Pooler (port 5432)
- Never use the direct connection string in production
- All schema changes go through `drizzle-kit push` — never manual SQL

## API Rules
- All API routes defined in `server/routes.ts`
- Always return consistent response shapes: `{ data: ... }` or `{ error: ... }`
- Never break existing endpoint URLs — frontend depends on them
- Authentication uses express-session — check auth middleware before adding protected routes

## Environment
- Local dev: `npm run dev` (loads `.env` automatically via --env-file flag)
- Never hardcode URLs — use environment variables
- Local runs on port 5000

## When Asked to Build a Feature
1. Read relevant existing code first — understand the pattern before writing new code
2. Follow existing patterns in the codebase
3. Make the smallest change that achieves the goal
4. List all files you plan to modify before making changes
5. Explain what you changed and why after completing

## When Asked to Fix a Bug
1. Identify the root cause first — don't just patch symptoms
2. Check if the same bug exists elsewhere in the codebase
3. Fix the root cause, not just the visible error
4. Explain what caused the bug and how the fix addresses it

## Commit Message Format
- `feat:` for new features
- `fix:` for bug fixes
- `refactor:` for code restructuring
- `style:` for UI/visual changes
- `docs:` for documentation
- `chore:` for maintenance tasks

## Two-Agent Workflow
- Primary agent (Codex/GPT): Day-to-day feature building, component work, API routes
- Backup agent (Claude Opus): Architecture decisions, complex refactors, debugging hard problems
- When stuck after 2 attempts — switch to backup agent and explain what was tried
